e in Methodology -- t20. Travels of Corn and Squash -- t21. Pre-Columbian Maize in Asia -- t22. Some Problems of Interpreting Transoceanic Dispersal of the New World Cottons -- t23. Phaseolus: Diffusion and Centers of Origin -- t24. Commentary: Section III -- tConclusions -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tLIST OF CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhether humans crossed the seas between the Old World and the New in the times before Columbus is a tantalizing question that has long excited scholarly interest and tempted imaginations the world over. From the myths of Atlantis and Mu to the more credible, perhaps, but hardly less romantic tales of Viking ships and Buddhist missionaries, people have speculated upon what is, after all, not simply a question of contact, but of the nature and growth of civilization itself. To the specialist, it is an important question indeed. If people in the Western Hemisphere and in the Eastern Hemisphere developed their cultures more or less independently from the end of the last Ice Age until the voyages of Columbus, the remarkable similarities between New World and Old World cultures reveal something important about the evolution of culture. If, on the other hand, there were widespread or sustained contacts between the hemispheres in pre-Columbian times, these contacts represent events of vast significance to the prehistory and history of humanity. Originally delivered at a symposium held in May 1968, during the national meeting of the Society for American Archaeology, the papers presented here, by scholars eminent in the field, offer differing points of view and considerable evidence on the pros and cons of pre-Columbian contact between the Old World and the New. Various kinds of data—archaeological, botanical, geographical, and historical—are brought to bear on the problem, with provocative and original results. Introductory and concluding remarks by the editors pull together and evaluate the evidence and suggest ground rules for future studies of this sort. Man across the Sea provides no final answers as to whether people from Asia, Africa, or Europe visited the American Indian before Columbus. It does, however, present new evidence, suggested lines of approach, and a fresh attempt to delineate the problems involved and to establish acceptable canons of evidence for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Herbert G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeirne, Daniel Randall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlake, Leonard W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorhegyi, Stephan F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrand, Donald D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, George F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, Hugh C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoran, Jr., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Clinton R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEkholm, Gordon F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHedrick, B. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeffreys, M. D. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJett, Stephen C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKehoe, Alice B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelley, David H., econtributor.4c